You will need to decide if you will plant in the ground (not suggested) or in containers. A raised bed garden is ideal, the length of the fence. It helps the plant from spreading and also creates a living privacy fence rather quickly! Once sown in soil, sunchoke is almost impossible to eradicate. Please plant responsibly. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ad/Grow-Sunchokes-or-Jerusalem-Artichokes-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Grow-Sunchokes-or-Jerusalem-Artichokes-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ad/Grow-Sunchokes-or-Jerusalem-Artichokes-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Grow-Sunchokes-or-Jerusalem-Artichokes-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
